  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to implement\n\n2. United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (UNTOC)\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigation and prosecution\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets international banking standards for preventing money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank regulations\n- Provide framework and assessment mechanisms for anti-money laundering practices\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish comprehensive regulations for EU member states\n\n6. The Palermo Convention\n- Focuses on preventing organized crime and money laundering\n\nThese laws and conventions typically require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Implement customer due diligence procedures\n- Facilitate international cooperation in investigations\n- Create financial intelligence units\n\nWhile these are international standards, actual enforcement occurs at national levels through specific country laws and regulations.",
